If I were to describe what it feels like to fly a small plane, I would say it's like driving a motorcycle/at-terrain vehicle and a boat combined, at 4000 feet in the air.
On the ground, situations can change rapidly. There is a degree of instability on the ground, which requires motorcycles/all-terrain vehicles.
Moreover, you might not know that when driving an airplane on the ground, you control the direction with your feet, not with a joystick. It uses rudder pedals and brakes. It's not like a car.
While flying in the air, you will feel the turbulence and shaking, much like riding a boat on water. Although you can control the plane, at times the air currents may leave you feeling a bit disoriented, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just as sailors adapt to navigating the sea.
Regarding this, there is also a random fun fact:
Flying is very exhausting. Today my back and legs are sore to a great extent, feeling as if I had gone to the gym and worked out.
This is not as simple as going for a drive on a Sunday. To me, a novice, it more resembles a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, Happy Saturday. Welcome to 4000 feet in the air.
I will fly again tomorrow, and we will practice stall and slow flight.
The weather today was not very stable but super interesting. We practiced slow flight and stalling. Our ground speed dropped to 16 mph at one point, while our airspeed was still 65 mph.
Today the weather is sunny, although there's a bit of mist at high altitudes, the visibility is still great.
